#############################
# Mindstone Rebel – Example Environment
#############################

# Copy this file to `.env.local` and fill in real values for local
# development and for running packaging commands like `npm run package`
# and `npm run dist`.

# RudderStack analytics (required for runtime config generation)
#
# - RUDDERSTACK_WRITE_KEY: Source write key from your RudderStack workspace.
# - RUDDERSTACK_DATA_PLANE_URL: Data plane URL for that workspace.
#
# Use the special value `DISABLED` to keep analytics turned off while still
# allowing `npm run generate:runtime-config`, `npm run package`, and
# `npm run dist` to succeed. Any other non-empty values are treated as a real
# RudderStack configuration and will be validated at app launch.

RUDDERSTACK_WRITE_KEY=DISABLED
RUDDERSTACK_DATA_PLANE_URL=DISABLED

# OAuth client credentials
#
# OAuth client credentials are required for any provider you want to enable.
# Get them by registering your OAuth app at the provider's developer console.
# In OSS builds, Google, Slack, HubSpot, and Microsoft can now be configured
# in-app from Settings or onboarding. Environment variables remain a
# power-user/CI override and win over in-app values.
# There are no embedded client IDs, client secrets, or fallback defaults in OSS builds.
# See: docs/project/OAUTH_CONNECTOR_EXTERNALIZATION_PRINCIPLES.md

# Google Workspace (required for Google Workspace OAuth and token refresh)
# GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=your_google_oauth_client_id
# GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET=your_google_oauth_client_secret

# Slack (required for Slack OAuth on desktop and cloud-service)
# SLACK_CLIENT_ID=your_slack_oauth_client_id
# SLACK_CLIENT_SECRET=your_slack_oauth_client_secret

# Microsoft 365 (required for Microsoft OAuth; public-client PKCE flow, no client secret)
# MICROSOFT_CLIENT_ID=your_microsoft_public_client_id

# HubSpot (required for HubSpot OAuth and token refresh)
# HUBSPOT_CLIENT_ID=your_hubspot_oauth_client_id
# HUBSPOT_CLIENT_SECRET=your_hubspot_oauth_client_secret

# GitHub (required for GitHub OAuth)
# GITHUB_CLIENT_ID=your_github_oauth_client_id
# GITHUB_CLIENT_SECRET=your_github_oauth_client_secret

# DigitalOcean (required for DigitalOcean OAuth and token refresh)
# DIGITAL_OCEAN_CLIENT_ID=your_digital_ocean_oauth_client_id
# DIGITAL_OCEAN_CLIENT_SECRET=your_digital_ocean_oauth_client_secret

# Salesforce (required for Salesforce OAuth and jsforce token refresh)
# SALESFORCE_CLIENT_ID=your_salesforce_connected_app_client_id
# SALESFORCE_CLIENT_SECRET=your_salesforce_connected_app_client_secret

# Plaud (required for Plaud OAuth and token refresh)
# PLAUD_CLIENT_ID=your_plaud_oauth_client_id
# PLAUD_CLIENT_SECRET=your_plaud_oauth_client_secret

# Discourse needs no OAuth client credentials: it uses Discourse's built-in
# User API Key flow (Rebel self-generates a per-connection key pair at connect
# time), so there is no DISCOURSE_CLIENT_ID / DISCOURSE_CLIENT_SECRET to set.

# OpenRouter (optional/reserved; current PKCE setup uses OpenRouter's code exchange)
# OPENROUTER_CLIENT_ID=your_openrouter_oauth_client_id

# Disable all analytics (useful for local testing and CI)
#
# Set to `true` or `1` to prevent any analytics events from being sent.
# This is checked at runtime, so it works with packaged builds.
# DISABLE_ANALYTICS=true

# Mindstone Managed Cloud
#
# Fly.io API token used by the Mindstone Managed cloud provider to
# provision and manage cloud instances on behalf of @example.com users.
# Only needed when the managedCloudEnabled feature flag is active.
#
# MINDSTONE_MANAGED_PROVIDER_TOKEN=your_fly_api_token_here

# Local Backend Development
#
# Point the app at a locally-running rebel-platform backend.
# Recommended: Use `npm run dev:local` instead of setting this manually.
# Default: https://rebel.mindstone.com (production)
#
# REBEL_API_URL=http://localhost:8080

# OAuth-MCP redirect URIs (self-hosting overrides)
#
# The bundled OAuth MCP connectors default to Mindstone's hosted OAuth worker.
# Override these only when you are running a self-hosted worker that implements
# the same callback/start routes. HubSpot uses local loopback ports (8081-8084),
# not the worker, so it does not need an env var here.
#
# Production defaults:
# SLACK_REDIRECT_URI=https://rebel-auth.mindstone.com/slack/callback
# MICROSOFT_REDIRECT_URI=https://rebel-auth.mindstone.com/microsoft/callback
# SALESFORCE_REDIRECT_URI=https://rebel-auth.mindstone.com/salesforce/callback
# PLAUD_REDIRECT_URI=https://rebel-auth.mindstone.com/plaud/callback
# GITHUB_REDIRECT_URI=https://rebel-auth.mindstone.com/github/callback
# DIGITAL_OCEAN_REDIRECT_URI=https://rebel-auth.mindstone.com/digitalocean/callback
# OPENROUTER_REDIRECT_URI=https://rebel-auth.mindstone.com/openrouter/callback
# OPENROUTER_AUTH_START_URL=https://rebel-auth.mindstone.com/openrouter/start

# Sentry error-reporting DSN
#
# The DSN is a public identifier (safe to embed in shipped binaries), but it
# is NOT hardcoded in this repo (OSS scrub). Delivery per build type:
#
# - Commercial release builds: the `SENTRY_DSN` GitHub secret is injected as
#   `VITE_SENTRY_DSN` / `MAIN_VITE_SENTRY_DSN` on the Electron Forge steps in
#   .github/workflows/release.yml; Vite inlines it into the main + renderer
#   bundles at build time (only VITE_*-prefixed vars reach import.meta.env in
#   packaged builds). release.yml fails loudly if the secret is missing or the
#   built bundles lack the DSN (scripts/check-built-bundle-sentry-dsn.mjs).
# - Local dev: off by default. To test Sentry locally, set SENTRY_DSN below
#   (raw process.env works in the dev main process) plus SENTRY_ENABLED=1.
# - OSS builds: never read from env — user-supplied via settings.telemetry only.
#
# See docs/project/ERROR_MONITORING_AND_SENTRY.md.
#
# SENTRY_DSN=https://<key>@<org>.ingest.us.sentry.io/<project-id>

# Sentry attachment fetcher (for AI agents during bug investigation)
#
# A Sentry User Auth Token used by `scripts/fetch-sentry-attachment.ts` to
# download non-image bug-report attachments (filtered-logs.ndjson,
# diagnostic-summary.md, update-state JSON, etc.) that the Sentry MCP
# returns as opaque embedded resources.
#
# The Sentry MCP is still the primary path; this is the fallback that lets
# agents read JSON / NDJSON / Markdown attachments to disk so they can
# Read them. Image attachments (screenshots) work through the MCP as-is
# and don't need this token.
#
# Setup (one time, ~3 minutes):
#   1. https://mindstone.sentry.io/settings/account/api/auth-tokens/
#   2. Create a User Auth Token with scopes: event:read, org:read, project:read.
#      It MUST be a User Auth Token (or an Internal Integration) — Organization
#      Auth Tokens (the `sntrys_...` ones used for releases/sourcemaps) have a
#      fixed CI scope set that can't carry event:read/org:read, so they 403 on
#      these read endpoints.
#   3. Paste the token below in your local .env.local
#
# SENTRY_AUTH_TOKEN=<your-sentry-user-auth-token>
#
# NOTE: This is a LOCAL dev token. The CI "Sentry Outcome Monitor" workflow uses
# a separate repo secret, SENTRY_MONITOR_AUTH_TOKEN (scope org:read), not this.
# See docs/project/ERROR_MONITORING_AND_SENTRY.md.
